observations.recommendation:
Submit justification/s on charging those items noted to BGCM;

Stop the charging of fuel which were used for purposes that are not in accordance with Item 3.6 of DBM Local Budget Circular No. 125 instead, spend the amounts to PPAs that can help strengthen the prevention and mitigation measures; 

Adhere strictly to the provisions of DBM Local Budget Circular No. 125 in the utilization of the BGCM Fund of the Municipality; 

Require the MDDRMO to monitor the trips of the Municipality owned vehicles particularly those being used in the prevention and mitigation of the threat of COVID 19 and instruct the drivers assigned to each vehicle or will be using the vehicle to properly fill out the Driver’s Trip Ticket and indicate the purpose; and

Require the MDDRMO, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to coordinate to each other so that fuel to be used are properly charged to the right fund.

To facilitate the conduct and completion of the RPCPPE and RPCI and to ensure that the PPE and Inventory balances reflected in the FS are fairly presented;

a.	Require the different offices to list down all PPE’s located in their area of vicinity or the PPEs they are accountable for per Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment as well as their unissued supplies at year-end;

b.	Pending the assignment of the full time GSO, create an inventory team and direct the concerned personnel to consolidate the said list and set a timetable indicating the timelines when to coordinate with the Accounting Office for reconciliation and when to conduct the actual physical count for PPE and Inventory for CY 2021;

c.	All identified unserviceable properties for disposal shall be reported in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) and shall be prepared with a journal voucher by the Accounting Office after its proper disposal;

d.	Request relief from accountability with available supporting evidence for lost properties, if warranted; and

e.	Maintain accounting and property records for PPE and Inventories already counted physically and all of its additions during the year.

a.	Immediately submit justification for the non-submission of the complete financial transactions;

b.	Direct the assigned personnel to stamped “PAID” the disbursement voucher, payroll and liquidation reports and all its supporting documents with date and signature after payment is made to prevent possible re-use of the same on similar transactions, thereby strengthening the internal control system of the Municipality;

c.	Direct the requesting office/unit to make use of the Appendix 31 of GAM Volume II new format of Disbursement Voucher with Box F for accounting journal entry and attach in the face of the DV the documentary checklist per COA Circular 2012-001 according to their nature of transactions to ensure completeness of supporting documents and accurate accounting classification before processing and payment;

d.	Completely and appropriately fill up Inspection and Acceptance Reports; 

e.	Make use of Appendices 38 and 39 of GAM for LGU Volume II for its Report of Checks Issued and Report of cash Disbursements and ensure complete and appropriate fill-up; and

f.	Ensure that transactions are supported with complete documentation, and that said supporting attachments are duly filled up and signed by the relevant signatories.

Submit justification for the failure to adhere to the provisions of EO No. 77 and COA Circular No. 97-02 regarding the traveling allowance claims and non-liquidation of cash advances;

Direct the concerned government official to refund the excess claim of ₱11,861.00;

Strictly comply with the provisions on the grant, liquidation, and traveling allowance claims on cash advances; and

To avoid issuance of Notices of Suspensions and/ or Notices of Disallowance, immediately submit the necessary attachments for the liquidation of cash advances in order for the audit team to determine the validity and propriety of the travels.

Submit justification/s regarding the existence of personnel with delinquent loan repayments;

Require the monthly deduction from the monthly compensation of employees the loan amortizations due to GSIS and remit the same in accordance with Sections 14.2 and 14.3 of RA No. 8291 to avoid the occurrence of delinquent loan repayments from members; and

Require the employees/personnel listed with delinquent loan repayments to coordinate with GSIS for the reconciliation of their loan accounts and request for loan restructuring.

a. issue demand letters to Accountable Officers with unliquidated cash advances;

b. requires all AOs to fully settle their previous balances before they are allowed a new cash advance in accordance to the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002; and

secure documentary requirements for dormant unliquidated cash advances as provided under COA Circular 2016-005, if warranted, request for write-off and prepare adjusting journal entries when request is granted.

We recommended that the Management:
Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers in order to keep track of all the sundry details in the receivables, payables, and property accounts;
Strictly observe honest, accurate, consistent and transparent recording in its books of accounts by exerting effort on the retrieval of records/reports from respective files that would establish the details of transactions in order to reclassify to its appropriate accounts;
Considering the amount involved, make it as a top priority to create a taskforce who will be relieved from their regular duties to devote their full time in the retrieval of documents and/or hire additional manpower and submit a timetable showing the schedule of activities in retrieving the documents, reconciling reports and adjusting the unreconciled beginning balances to its appropriate accounts for an accurate and reliable financial reporting; and putting into consideration the following:
In the case of receivables, exhaust all possible means to collect the receivables. Otherwise, request for write-off in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005;
In the case of Property, Plant and Equipment, conduct physical count of the LGU’s properties. Provide adjusting entries to transfer completed projects and request for disposal of unserviceable properties;
In the case of payables, exhaust all possible means to pay off the LGU’s accounts. Otherwise, request for write-off in accordance with the provisions of the COA Circular 2016-005;
In the case of fund transfer (due to and due from), coordinate with the partner agencies with whom the funds were transferred and liquidate it.

We recommended that the Management:
Strictly comply with the provisions of Section 4.c of CSC Resolution No. 02-0790 dated June 5, 2002 and stop the practice of hiring personnel through contract of service to perform functions pertaining to regular and/or vacant plantilla positions;
Before payment of compensation, require the submission of an accomplishment report to support that the hired contract of service personnel is/was able to perform the deliverables required from her;
Strictly comply with the prescribed rate in compliance with Section 6.6 of LBC 132; and
Looking forward, ensure that the pro-forma contract of service include an attestation on the part of the person to be hired that he/she is not related within the fourth degree in the case of LGUs of consanguinity or affinity with the contracting officer and the appointing authority of the hiring agency; and that he/she has not been previously dismissed from the service by reason of an administrative case in compliance with Item 4b of CSC Resolution No. 02-1480 dated November 12, 2002.

We recommended that the Management assign personnel for the constant monitoring and general supervision over each component Barangays to ensure that every barangays act within the scope of their prescribed powers and functions by:
Monitoring their submission of reports to the Municipality complete with the required supporting documentation within the deadline set by the Municipal Accountant and as prescribed by the Manual on Financial Management of Barangays and send demand letters, if warranted;
Conducting re-orientation seminar focusing on the Appendix C of the manual which provides for the Matrix of Reports and Forms showing the record/report title, who shall submit or accomplish the report, number of copies to be distributed and to whom it will be distributed, the frequency and due date of submission and the remarks or purpose of the record/report, to know the extent of their duties and responsibilities;
Revisit the personnel complement in the Accounting Unit to ensure timely, complete and accurate preparation and submission of Barangay Financial Statements to the office of the auditor; and
Require explanation/ justification from Barangays who still failed to comply despite constant monitoring and supervision.

We recommended to Management the following improvement opportunities to wit:
Attach a copy of documentary checklist in every DV as a guide on its proper supporting attachment. Also, direct all requesting personnel/department to ensure that all details on the supporting documents are completely and thoroughly filled up;
Exercise due diligence in the filling up of details/information in the Request for Quotations, Inspection and Acceptance Reports, and Purchase Orders to ensure accurate and reliable document/report;
Submit Purchase Orders and Inspection and Acceptance Reports to COA within the prescribed period as required under COA Circular No. 2009-001 and COA Circular No. 95-006;
For payment through reimbursements, ensure that the payee of the Official receipt is “LGU Tubay”, and prepare a summary of expenses, stamp the OR as paid to preclude re-use; and
Submit the required Monthly Report for Official Travels per vehicle and the consolidated Monthly Reports on Fuel Consumption of government vehicles along with its complete supporting attachments in order for the audit team to review the reasonableness of fuel consumed during the period.

We recommended that the Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the staffing of the Municipal Accounting Office are assigned with personnel who can help hasten the preparation and submission of financial reports;
Revisit the current system from SPIDC as compared by the eNGAS and eBudget from the COA and reconsider which system will really help facilitate systematic generation of financial reports;
Moreover, register from LBP we-access application to facilitate the prompt preparation of Bank Reconciliation Statements; and
Looking forward, strictly adhere to the prescribed period for submission of the required reports to facilitate immediate action on deficiencies noted.

Direct the Bids and Awards Committee to submit justification why competitive bidding was not used as the mode of procurement;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to make sure that supporting documents are proper, completely filled-up and signed as attested in box A of the disbursement voucher;

For future transactions, in the case of LGU – Tubay, a fourth class municipality, procurement and projects amounting to ₱100,000.00 and above shall be submitted to the Office of the Auditor for review.

